        heading: "What Is the NCIDQ and Why It Matters",
        body: "The National Council for Interior Design Qualification (NCIDQ) examination is the recognized standard for professional interior design competency in the United States and Canada. Passing the NCIDQ is required for licensure, certification, or registration in twenty-eight U.S. states and jurisdictions, all Canadian provinces, and the District of Columbia. It is also required or accepted by numerous professional organizations, including the American Society of Interior Designers (ASID), the International Interior Design Association (IIDA), and the Interior Designers of Canada (IDC), as a prerequisite for professional-level membership.\n\nThe NCIDQ exam validates that a designer possesses the knowledge, skills, and abilities necessary to protect public health, safety, and welfare in the practice of interior design. This health-safety-welfare mandate is the legal foundation for interior design regulation, just as it is for architecture, engineering, and other licensed professions. The exam tests competency across the breadth of professional practice, from programming and space planning through design development, construction documentation, and contract administration.\n\nFor aspiring designers, the NCIDQ represents a significant career milestone. NCIDQ certificate holders report higher average salaries, greater job opportunities, and enhanced professional credibility compared to non-certified designers. Many architecture and design firms require or prefer NCIDQ certification for senior design positions. The certification is portable across jurisdictions, meaning a designer certified in California can use the credential to pursue licensure in New York, Texas, Florida, or any other regulated state without retaking the examination. This portability provides career flexibility that is particularly valuable in today's mobile workforce.",
