        body: "While every content area on the NCIDQ exam deserves attention, certain topics carry more weight and appear more frequently across all three sections. Building codes and accessibility standards are tested extensively. Candidates must know the International Building Code (IBC) provisions relevant to interior design, including occupancy classifications, means of egress requirements (corridor widths, exit distances, door hardware, signage), fire-resistance ratings for interior finishes (ASTM E84 flame-spread and smoke-development indices), and plumbing fixture count calculations based on occupancy type and load. ADA Accessibility Guidelines for dimensions, clearances, and accessible route requirements appear in virtually every exam section.\n\nConstruction knowledge is another heavily tested area. Candidates should understand wall types (load-bearing vs. partition, fire-rated assemblies, STC and CAC ratings for acoustical partitions), ceiling systems (direct-applied, suspended grid, specialty ceilings), flooring systems (substrate requirements, transition details, material properties), and door and hardware specifications (fire-rated door assemblies, hardware functions, keying systems). The exam tests both conceptual understanding and specific technical knowledge, so candidates must know not just that fire-rated walls exist but the specific UL design numbers, penetration sealing requirements, and head-of-wall details that make them perform.\n\nProfessional practice questions address ethical responsibilities, contract types (AIA and ASID standard forms), liability and insurance, fee structures, and project delivery methods. Sustainability topics have increased in prominence, with questions addressing LEED credit categories, indoor air quality standards, VOC emission limits, and life-cycle assessment concepts. Lighting fundamentals, including lamp types, color temperature, CRI, foot-candle recommendations, and lighting calculation methods, appear across all sections. Prioritizing these high-frequency content areas while maintaining adequate coverage of the full exam outline maximizes the candidate's probability of achieving a passing score."
